Devon generally experiences what meteorologists, in their infinite wisdom, term a "cool oceanic climate." This designation is heavily influenced by the benevolent, or perhaps merely persistent, presence of the [North Atlantic Drift](/North_Atlantic_Drift). In the depths of winter, snowfall is, for the most part, a relatively uncommon spectacle away from the higher elevations, though one can always anticipate a few notable exceptions, just to keep things interesting. The county typically enjoys mild summers, punctuated by occasional, fleeting warm spells and, with a certain predictability, cool, rainy interludes. Winters are generally cool, though Devon frequently lays claim to some of the mildest winters globally for its relatively high latitude, boasting average daily maximum temperatures in January of a rather temperate 8°C (46°F).

Rainfall, as one might expect from such a varied topography, exhibits significant disparities across the county. It can range dramatically from over 2,000 millimetres (79 inches) on the more exposed parts of [Dartmoor](/Dartmoor), where the clouds seem to cling with a particular tenacity, to a mere 750 millimetres (30 inches) in the more fortunate [rain shadow](/Rain_shadow) along the coast in southeastern Devon and around [Exeter](/Exeter). Similarly, the amount of available sunshine varies widely: the moors are, predictably, often cloaked in cloud, with the uplands near Princetown receiving fewer than 1,400 hours of sunshine annually. Conversely, the southeastern coast, particularly around [Brixham](/Brixham) and Berry Head, basks in over 1,800 hours annually, making it one of the sunniest locales in the entire United Kingdom. When westerly or south-westerly winds prevail, accompanied by high pressure, the areas around [Torbay](/Torbay) and [Teignmouth](/Teignmouth) will frequently experience warm conditions and extended periods of sunshine, a phenomenon attributed to the protective shelter offered by the surrounding high ground—a classic demonstration of the [Foehn wind](/Foehn_wind) effect. Nature, it seems, has its own subtle preferences.

