## Ecology

![Ponies grazing on Exmoor near Brendon, North Devon](/File:Exmoor_ponies_near_Brendon,_Devon.jpg)
Ponies grazing on Exmoor near [Brendon](/Brendon), [North Devon](/North_Devon). Creatures of habit, indifferent to human observation.

The sheer diversity of habitats within Devon naturally fosters an equally wide array of wildlife, a complexity that often escapes casual notice (one might, for instance, consult [Dartmoor wildlife](/Dartmoor_wildlife) for a glimpse into this intricate web). A popular, if somewhat obsessive, challenge among devoted [birders](/Birders) is the attempt to identify over 100 distinct species within the county in a single day [citation needed]—a testament to both the avian richness and human tenacity. The county's precious wildlife is diligently safeguarded by a number of dedicated conservation organisations, notably the [Devon Wildlife Trust](/Devon_Wildlife_Trust), which oversees the protection and management of some 40 nature reserves. The Devon Bird Watching and Preservation Society, an organisation founded in 1928 and known since 2005 as "Devon Birds," stands as a venerable county bird society, committed to both the rigorous study and the active conservation of wild bird populations [24]. Furthermore, the [RSPB](/RSPB) maintains its own reserves within the county, and [Natural England](/Natural_England) bears the responsibility for over 200 of Devon's designated [Sites of Special Scientific Interest](/Sites_of_Special_Scientific_Interest) and [National Nature Reserves](/National_nature_reserves_in_England) [25], including the ecologically vital [Slapton Ley](/Slapton_Ley). The [Devon Bat Group](/Devon_Bat_Group), established in 1984, plays a crucial role in the conservation efforts for these often-misunderstood nocturnal mammals. The wildlife encountered in this region extends to a veritable cornucopia of insects, butterflies, and moths; among these, the rather striking [chequered skipper](/Carterocephalus_palaemon) butterfly warrants particular attention.

Devon serves as a national nexus for several species that are remarkably uncommon across the broader British landscape. These include the distinctive [cirl bunting](/Cirl_bunting); the elusive [greater horseshoe bat](/Greater_horseshoe_bat); the rare [Bechstein's bat](/Bechstein%27s_bat); and the vibrantly patterned [Jersey tiger moth](/Jersey_tiger_moth). It also holds the unique distinction of being the sole location on mainland Britain where the delicate sand crocus (*[Romulea columnae](/Romulea_columnae)*) can be found in its natural habitat—specifically at Dawlish Warren. Furthermore, the county is home to all six native British land reptile species, a testament to its diverse ecosystems and, in some cases, the success of reintroduction efforts. A more recent, and rather promising, reintroduction has seen the return of the [Eurasian beaver](/Eurasian_beaver), primarily along the [River Otter](/River_Otter,_Devon), a species whose ecological impact is still being carefully observed. Other rare species documented within Devon's waters include the delicate seahorses and the beautiful sea daffodil [26] [27].

The county's botany is exceptionally rich and varied, boasting several rare species that are found nowhere else in the British Isles apart from [Cornwall](/Cornwall)—a botanical kinship, if you will. Devon is geographically divided into two distinct [Watsonian vice-counties](/Watsonian_vice-counties): north and south. The boundary between them is an irregular line, meandering approximately across the higher elevations of [Dartmoor](/Dartmoor) before following the canal eastwards. Botanical records for the region stretch back to the 17th century, with significant early works such as the *Flora Devoniensis* by Jones and Kingston in 1829 [28]. A more general account was included in *[The Victoria History of the County of Devon](/Victoria_County_History)* (1906), and a comprehensive *Flora of Devon* was published in 1939 by [Keble Martin](/Keble_Martin) and Fraser [29]. The *Atlas of the Devon Flora* by Ivimey-Cook appeared in 1984, and a more recent *New Flora of Devon*, based on extensive fieldwork conducted between 2005 and 2014, was finally published in 2016 [30]. In a rather telling sign of changing global patterns, rising temperatures have led to Devon becoming the first place in modern Britain to successfully cultivate olives commercially [31]—a small victory, perhaps, against the inevitable march of time and climate.

In January 2024, ambitious plans were unveiled for the planting of over 100,000 trees across northern Devon, a concerted effort to bolster the region's [Celtic rainforests](/Celtic_rainforest). These cherished, yet increasingly imperilled, ecosystems are a vital part of the UK's natural heritage. The project aims to establish 50 hectares of new rainforest across three carefully selected sites, strategically planting trees in close proximity to existing rainforest areas along both the coast and inland. Among the diverse array of tree species slated for planting is the rare [Devon whitebeam](/Devon_whitebeam), a species notable for its unique method of reproduction and its fruit, which was once a popular local delicacy. This significant initiative is being spearheaded by the [National Trust](/National_Trust), with invaluable assistance from a network of dedicated volunteers and community groups, focusing its efforts on key locations within [Exmoor](/Exmoor), [Woolacombe](/Woolacombe), [Hartland](/Hartland,_Devon), and [Arlington Court](/Arlington_Court) [32]. A commendable, if perhaps Sisyphean, effort to preserve what remains.

## Demographics

### Ethnicity

For the overwhelming majority of Devon’s long and largely uneventful history, the population residing within the ceremonial county was, to put it mildly, ethnically homogeneous. It was, almost exclusively, composed of individuals of [White British](/White_British) ethnicity. However, the [2021 census](/United_Kingdom_Census_2021) revealed a slightly more complex picture, recording a usual resident population of 1,215,661 for the ceremonial county of Devon. This larger entity is, of course, administratively subdivided into the non-metropolitan county governed by [Devon County Council](/Devon_County_Council), which, in the 2021 census, accounted for 811,642 usual residents, and two distinct [unitary authorities](/Unitary_authorities_of_England): [Plymouth City Council](/Plymouth_City_Council), with 264,695 usual residents, and [Torbay Council](/Torbay_Council), with 139,324 usual residents. The 2021 census further detailed the ethnic composition of the ceremonial county of Devon as follows: 95.8% White; 1.6% Asian; 0.5% Black; 1.5% Mixed; and 0.6% Other.

*   White (95.8%): Comprising English, Welsh, Scottish, Northern Irish, or British (91.8%); Irish (0.5%); Gypsy or Irish Traveller (0.1%); Roma (0.1%); and Other White (3.4%). A rather granular breakdown, if one is interested in such minutiae.
*   Asian (1.6%): Including Indian (0.4%); Pakistani (0.1%); Bangladeshi (0.1%); Chinese (0.4%); and Other Asian (0.6%).
*   Black (0.5%): Consisting of African (0.3%); Caribbean (0.1%); and Other Black (0.1%).
*   Mixed (1.5%): A category encompassing White and Asian (0.5%); White and Black African (0.2%); White and Black Caribbean (0.3%); and Other Mixed or Multiple ethnic groups (0.4%).
*   Other (0.6%): Including Arab (0.2%) and Any other ethnic group (0.4%).

Note: Sub-group totals may not sum exactly to the group total due to rounding. Data for the ceremonial county are aggregated from its constituent unitary authorities. Such precision, one might argue, is often an illusion.

