## Ancient and medieval history

The region now known as Devon was, in the pre-Roman era, the ancient dominion of the [Dumnonii](/Dumnonii), a distinct [Celtic tribe](/Celtic_tribe) whose very name, as previously noted, translates rather evocatively to the "Deep Valley Dwellers." The western reaches of this territory, particularly those beyond [Exeter](/Exeter), remained notably less Romanised compared to the more thoroughly integrated parts of [Roman Britain](/Roman_Britain), largely due to its perceived remoteness within the province. Following the official withdrawal of Roman authority from Britain in AD 410, one of the prominent Dumnonii families, seizing the opportunity presented by the vacuum of power, made a rather ambitious attempt to establish a dynastic rule, effectively positioning themselves as the new Kings of Dumnonii [39]. A familiar pattern of ambition filling an empty throne.

[Celtic paganism](/Celtic_paganism) and the various [Roman practices](/Religion_in_ancient_Rome) were, predictably, the earliest known religious traditions within Devon. However, by the mid-fourth century AD, [Christianity](/Christianity) began its slow, inexorable introduction to the region [40] [citation needed]. During the subsequent [Sub-Roman period](/Sub-Roman_Britain), the Christian church throughout the [British Isles](/British_Isles) developed certain distinct practices that diverged somewhat from the prevailing [Latin Christianity](/Latin_Christianity) of continental Europe. This unique expression of faith is now commonly referred to as [Celtic Christianity](/Celtic_Christianity) [41] [42] [43]. Despite these localised variations, it is crucial to note that the Celtic church always maintained communion with the broader [Roman Catholic Church](/Roman_Catholic_Church). Many revered [Cornish saints](/Cornish_saints) are also commemorated with a surprising frequency in Devon, their legends, church dedications, and place-names woven into the very fabric of the landscape. [Saint Petroc](/Saint_Petroc), for instance, is said to have traversed Devon, where ancient dedications to him are, perhaps counter-intuitively, even more numerous than in [Cornwall](/Cornwall)—a probable seventeen (plus [Timberscombe](/Timberscombe) just across the [Somerset](/Somerset) border), compared to Cornwall's mere five. The geographical placement of churches bearing his name, including one nestled within the ancient Roman walls of [Exeter](/Exeter), almost invariably indicates their proximity to the coast, a pragmatic reflection of the maritime travel routes prevalent in those distant days. The Devonian villages of [Petrockstowe](/Petrockstowe) and [Newton St Petroc](/Newton_St_Petroc) also bear his name, and, rather significantly, the [flag of Devon](/Flag_of_Devon) itself is dedicated to Saint Petroc.

The precise history of [Christianity](/Christianity) in the Southwest of England remains, regrettably, somewhat shrouded in the mists of time. While parts of the historic county of Devon were incorporated into the diocese of [Wessex](/Kingdom_of_Wessex), the ecclesiastical organisation of the more distinctly Celtic areas remains largely unknown. Around 703, Devon and [Cornwall](/Cornwall) were brought together under the separate diocese of Sherborne. By 900, this arrangement was again divided into two, with the Devon bishop establishing his seat at Tawton (now [Bishop's Tawton](/Bishop%27s_Tawton)) from 905, and subsequently at [Crediton](/Crediton) from 912—the birthplace, one notes, of the revered [Saint Boniface](/Saint_Boniface). [Lyfing](/Lyfing,_Abbot_of_Tavistock) assumed the role of [Bishop of Crediton](/Bishop_of_Crediton) in 1027, and shortly thereafter, in a move of consolidation, also became [Bishop of Cornwall](/Bishop_of_Cornwall).

The two dioceses of Crediton and Cornwall, which collectively encompassed Devon and Cornwall, were eventually united under [Edward the Confessor](/Edward_the_Confessor) by Lyfing's successor, [Bishop Leofric](/Bishop_Leofric). Leofric, who had previously served as Bishop of Crediton, was appointed the first Bishop of [Exeter](/Exeter) under Edward the Confessor, with Exeter formally established as his cathedral city in 1050. Initially, the venerable abbey church of St Mary and St Peter, originally founded by [Athelstan](/%C3%86thelstan) in 932 and subsequently rebuilt in 1019, served as the interim cathedral. A rather pragmatic arrangement, one might observe, for a period of transition.

Devon, throughout the tumultuous [Middle Ages](/Later_Middle_Ages), found itself repeatedly falling under the shifting political influence of various noble houses, most notably the Courtenays, who held the esteemed title of [Earl of Devon](/Earl_of_Devon). During the brutal [Wars of the Roses](/Wars_of_the_Roses), the county was a battleground of competing allegiances, with prominent magnates including the aforementioned Earl of Devon, [William Bonville, 1st Baron Bonville](/William_Bonville,_1st_Baron_Bonville), and [Humphrey Stafford, 1st Earl of Devon](/Humphrey_Stafford,_1st_Earl_of_Devon), whose extensive influence stretched from [Cornwall](/Cornwall) all the way to Wiltshire. Following the decisive year of 1485, one of the county's most influential figures emerged in the form of [Henry VII](/Henry_VII)'s courtier, [Robert Willoughby, 1st Baron Willoughby de Broke](/Robert_Willoughby,_1st_Baron_Willoughby_de_Broke) [44]. Such were the fickle tides of medieval power.

## Later history

In 1549, the deeply divisive [Prayer Book Rebellion](/Prayer_Book_Rebellion) erupted, a conflict that tragically resulted in the deaths of thousands of individuals from both Devon and [Cornwall](/Cornwall). This period marked a profound shift in the religious landscape of the county. During the broader [English Reformation](/English_Reformation), churches throughout Devon officially severed ties with Rome and became affiliated with the newly established [Church of England](/Church_of_England). From the latter half of the sixteenth century onwards, a fervent strain of Protestantism—often labelled 'puritanism'—became increasingly entrenched in certain pockets of Devon, while other districts within the county stubbornly maintained a more conservative, traditional religious outlook. These burgeoning theological and cultural divisions would, with a certain inevitability, become brutally apparent during the [English Civil War](/English_Civil_War) of 1642–46, a conflict that saw the county fractured along these very religious and cultural fault lines [45]. The [Methodism](/Methodism) espoused by [John Wesley](/John_Wesley) proved remarkably popular among the working classes of Devon during the 19th century. Methodist chapels rapidly transformed into vital social centres, with their male voice choirs and other church-affiliated groups playing a central role in the social fabric of working-class Devonian life. Methodism, even today, continues to play a significant, if diminished, part in the religious landscape of Devon, though the county has, rather predictably, mirrored the broader post-World War II decline in British religious observance.

The [Diocese of Exeter](/Diocese_of_Exeter) remains the Anglican diocese encompassing the entirety of Devon. The [Roman Catholic Diocese of Plymouth](/Roman_Catholic_Diocese_of_Plymouth) was established somewhat later, in the mid-19th century [46], reflecting the gradual re-establishment of the Catholic hierarchy in England.

## Governance

• See also: [2025 Devon County Council election](/2025_Devon_County_Council_election) and [Local Government Act 2010](/Local_Government_Act_2010)

![County Hall, Exeter. Headquarters for Devon County Council.](/File:Devon_County_Council_Headquarters_-_geograph.org.uk_-_1211756.jpg)
County Hall, [Exeter](/Exeter). Headquarters for [Devon County Council](/Devon_County_Council). A building, one presumes, where decisions are made, or at least discussed at length.

The administrative core and traditional capital of Devon is the city of [Exeter](/Exeter). However, the county's largest city, [Plymouth](/Plymouth)—a venerable historic port—along with the urban agglomeration of [Torbay](/Torbay) (which, rather awkwardly, includes the largest town in Devon and the *de facto* capital of Torbay, [Torquay](/Torquay), as well as [Paignton](/Paignton) and [Brixham](/Brixham)), have operated as independent [unitary authorities](/Unitary_authorities_of_England) since 1998. This administrative separation means they are distinct from the remainder of Devon, which falls under the direct governance of [Devon County Council](/Devon_County_Council) for the purposes of local administration.

[Devon County Council](/Devon_County_Council) currently finds itself in a state of [no overall control](/No_overall_control), a political landscape that often leads to prolonged debate rather than decisive action. The current political representation of its 60 councillors is distributed as follows: 27 [Liberal Democrats](/Liberal_Democrats_(UK)), 16 [Reform UK](/Reform_UK), 7 [Conservatives](/Conservative_Party_(UK)), 6 [Greens](/Green_Party_of_England_and_Wales), and 4 [Independents](/Independent_politician) [47]. A rather fragmented assembly, one might note, reflecting the diverse, and often conflicting, desires of the electorate.

At the most recent [2024 general election](/2024_United_Kingdom_general_election), Devon returned a somewhat varied political contingent to the [House of Commons](/House_of_Commons_of_the_United_Kingdom): six [Liberal Democrats](/Liberal_Democrats_(UK)), four [Conservatives](/Conservative_Party_(UK)), and three [Labour](/Labour_Party_(UK)) MPs [48]. A shifting mosaic of representation, as is the nature of democratic processes.

### Hundreds

Historically, and for centuries, Devon was meticulously subdivided into 32 distinct [hundreds](/Hundred_(county_subdivision)) [49]. These ancient administrative divisions, each with its own unique history and character, included: [Axminster](/Axminster_Hundred), [Bampton](/Bampton_Hundred), [Black Torrington](/Black_Torrington_Hundred), [Braunton](/Braunton_Hundred), [Cliston](/Cliston_Hundred), [Coleridge](/Coleridge_Hundred), [Colyton](/Colyton_Hundred), [Crediton](/Crediton_Hundred), [East Budleigh](/East_Budleigh_Hundred), [Ermington](/Ermington_Hundred), [Exminster](/Exminster_Hundred), [Fremington](/Fremington_Hundred), [Halberton](/Halberton_Hundred), [Hartland](/Hartland_Hundred), [Hayridge](/Hayridge_Hundred), [Haytor](/Haytor_Hundred), [Hemyock](/Hemyock_Hundred), [Lifton](/Lifton_Hundred), [North Tawton and Winkleigh](/North_Tawton_and_Winkleigh_Hundred), [Ottery](/Ottery_Hundred), [Plympton](/Plympton_Hundred), [Roborough](/Roborough_Hundred), [Shebbear](/Shebbear_Hundred), [Shirwell](/Shirwell_Hundred), [South Molton](/South_Molton_Hundred), [Stanborough](/Stanborough_Hundred), [Tavistock](/Tavistock_Hundred), [Teignbridge](/Teignbridge_Hundred), [Tiverton](/Tiverton_Hundred), [West Budleigh](/West_Budleigh_Hundred), [Witheridge](/Witheridge_Hundred), and [Wonford](/Wonford_Hundred). These names, though perhaps arcane to modern ears, echo the deep historical roots of the county's governance.

### Combined County Authority

• Main article: [Devon and Torbay Combined County Authority](/Devon_and_Torbay_Combined_County_Authority)

In a move towards greater regional cohesion and, presumably, efficiency, [Devon County Council](/Devon_County_Council) and [Torbay Council](/Torbay_Council) have formally become constituent members of the Devon and Torbay Combined County Authority. This new entity has been granted devolved powers, covering critical areas such as transport, housing, skills development, and support for local businesses [50]. A consolidation of power, which may or may not lead to actual improvement.

The authority is composed of 12 members, a carefully balanced assembly. Six of these are constituent members, endowed with full voting rights, reflecting the primary stakeholders. Four are non-constituent members, who typically do not possess voting powers unless such rights are explicitly extended to them by the constituent members. Finally, two associate members complete the body, though they are, by design, unable to vote. [Devon County Council](/Devon_County_Council) and [Torbay Council](/Torbay_Council) each select half of the constituent members, ensuring equitable representation of their interests. Two of the non-constituent members are collectively chosen by the district councils of Devon, ensuring their voices, however faint, are heard. One non-constituent seat is specifically reserved for the [Devon and Cornwall Police and Crime Commissioner](/Devon_and_Cornwall_Police_and_Crime_Commissioner), a nod to the importance of law and order. The remaining non-constituent member and the two associate members are, rather democratically, elected by the constituent members of the authority [51] [52]. An intricate web of governance, designed to distribute, or perhaps merely diffuse, responsibility.

## Settlements

• Main articles: [List of places in Devon](/List_of_places_in_Devon) and [List of towns and cities in Devon by population](/List_of_towns_and_cities_in_Devon_by_population)

![The inner harbour, Brixham, south Devon, at low tide](/File:Brixham_Inner_Harbour.jpg)
The inner harbour, [Brixham](/Brixham), south Devon, at low tide. A scene of quiet industry, waiting for the sea to return.

The principal settlements that define the character of Devon are the venerable city of [Plymouth](/Plymouth), a historic port that now enjoys administrative independence, [Exeter](/Exeter), which retains its designation as the [county town](/County_town), and [Torbay](/Torbay), often promoted as the county's primary tourist hub. Devon's extensive coastline is, rather predictably, punctuated by a string of tourist resorts, many of which experienced rapid expansion and transformation with the advent of the railways in the 19th century. Notable examples include Dawlish, [Exmouth](/Exmouth,_Devon), and [Sidmouth](/Sidmouth) along the more sheltered south coast, and [Ilfracombe](/Ilfracombe) and [Lynmouth](/Lynmouth) on the wilder north. The [Torbay](/Torbay) conurbation, a sprawling urban mass comprising [Torquay](/Torquay), [Paignton](/Paignton), and [Brixham](/Brixham) on the south coast, now operates with administrative independence from the main county body. Inland, the rural landscape is dotted with traditional [market towns](/Market_town) such as [Barnstaple](/Barnstaple), [Bideford](/Bideford), [Honiton](/Honiton), [Newton Abbot](/Newton_Abbot), [Okehampton](/Okehampton), [Tavistock](/Tavistock,_Devon), [Totnes](/Totnes), and [Tiverton](/Tiverton,_Devon), each serving as a local centre for commerce and community.

The boundary with [Cornwall](/Cornwall), traditionally marked by the [River Tamar](/River_Tamar), has not always been as immutable as it appears today. Until the late 19th century, a handful of parishes in the [Torpoint](/Torpoint) area were, rather inconveniently, considered part of Devon. Furthermore, five parishes now firmly situated in north-east Cornwall remained part of Devon until the administrative reorganisation of 1974. Interestingly, for ecclesiastical purposes, these parishes were, even then, consistently placed within the [Archdeaconry of Cornwall](/Archdeaconry_of_Cornwall) and subsequently, in 1876, became part of the [Diocese of Truro](/Diocese_of_Truro). A testament to the enduring, and often confusing, interplay of secular and religious boundaries.

## Symbols

### Coat of arms

![The coat of arms of Devon County Council](/File:Coat_of_Arms_of_Devon_County_Council.svg)
The coat of arms of [Devon County Council](/Devon_County_Council). A rather formal declaration of identity, for those who appreciate such things.

Prior to 1926, the county of Devon lacked a formally established [coat of arms](/Coat_of_arms). Consequently, the arms of the venerable City of [Exeter](/Exeter) were frequently pressed into service to represent the broader county, a practice evident, for instance, in the badge of the [Devonshire Regiment](/Devonshire_Regiment). With the formation of a county council under the provisions of the [Local Government Act 1888](/Local_Government_Act_1888), the adoption of a common seal became a mandatory requirement. This initial seal incorporated three distinct shields, depicting the arms of Exeter alongside those of the council's first chairman and vice-chairman, [Lord Clinton](/Charles_Hepburn-Stuart-Forbes-Trefusis,_20th_Baron_Clinton) and the [Earl of Morley](/Earl_of_Morley), respectively [53]. A rather democratic, if visually cluttered, arrangement.

On 11 October 1926, the county council finally received a formal grant of arms from the august [College of Arms](/College_of_Arms). The central feature of the shield proudly displays a red crowned lion set against a silver field, a direct appropriation of the arms of [Richard Plantagenet, Earl of Cornwall](/Richard_Plantagenet,_Earl_of_Cornwall). The 'chief,' or upper section, of the shield depicts an ancient ship gracefully navigating waves, a clear and unambiguous homage to Devon's rich seafaring traditions. The chosen Latin motto, *Auxilio Divino* ('by Divine aid'), was adopted from none other than Sir [Francis Drake](/Francis_Drake), a figure whose exploits are inextricably linked with the county. The 1926 grant, however, was limited solely to the arms. It was not until 6 March 1962 that a further grant, encompassing a crest and supporters, was obtained. The crest features the head of a [Dartmoor Pony](/Dartmoor_Pony) emerging from a "Naval Crown," a distinctive form of crown fashioned from the sails and sterns of ships, traditionally associated with the [Royal Navy](/Royal_Navy). The supporters, guarding the shield, are a robust [Devon bull](/Devon_bull) and a mythical sea lion [54] [55]. A rather comprehensive symbolic ensemble, one might observe, leaving little to the imagination.

Following the 1974 reorganisation, [Devon County Council](/Devon_County_Council) opted for a more minimalist "ship silhouette" logo, a stylised adaptation of the ship emblem from its coat of arms. However, after the administrative secession of [Plymouth](/Plymouth) and [Torbay](/Torbay) in 1998, the council, perhaps in a fit of nostalgic pragmatism, reverted to using the full coat of arms. In April 2006, the council unveiled yet another new logo, intended for most routine, everyday applications, while graciously permitting the continued use of the coat of arms for "various civic purposes" [56] [57]. Such are the ever-shifting tides of corporate branding, even in local governance.

### Flag

• Main article: [Flag of Devon](/Flag_of_Devon)

![The flag of the historic county of Devon](/File:Flag_of_Devon.svg)
The flag of the historic county of Devon. A simple design, perhaps intended to avoid unnecessary complexity.

Devon, in a display of regional pride, also possesses its own distinctive flag, which has been dedicated to [Saint Petroc](/Saint_Petroc), a local [saint](/Saint) whose veneration extends throughout Devon and its neighbouring counties. The flag was officially adopted in 2003, the culmination of a public competition orchestrated by [BBC Radio Devon](/BBC_Radio_Devon). The winning design, conceived by website contributor Ryan Sealey, garnered a decisive 49% of the votes cast [58]. The colours chosen for the flag are those popularly, and perhaps rather predictably, identified with Devon. These hues are reflected, for instance, in the colours of the [University of Exeter](/University_of_Exeter), the county's [rugby union](/Rugby_union) team, and the historic Green and White flag famously flown by the first [Viscount Exmouth](/Viscount_Exmouth) during the [Bombardment of Algiers](/Bombardment_of_Algiers_(1816)) (a relic now proudly displayed at the Teign Valley Museum). They are also echoed in the colours of one of the county's [association football](/Association_football) teams, [Plymouth Argyle](/Plymouth_Argyle). On 17 October 2006, the flag was ceremoniously hoisted for the very first time outside County Hall in [Exeter](/Exeter), a symbolic gesture to mark Local Democracy Week, thereby receiving official recognition from the county council [59]. More recently, in 2019, [Devon County Council](/Devon_County_Council), with the full endorsement of both the Anglican and Catholic churches in Exeter and Plymouth, officially acknowledged [Saint Boniface](/Saint_Boniface) as the Patron Saint of Devon [60]. A dual patronage, one might observe, for a county with a complex spiritual heritage.

## Place names and customs

![The beach at Westward Ho!, North Devon, looking north towards the shared estuary of the rivers Taw and Torridge](/File:Westward_Ho_01.jpg)
The beach at [Westward Ho!](/Westward_Ho!), North Devon, looking north towards the shared [estuary](/Estuary) of the rivers [Taw](/River_Taw) and [Torridge](/River_Torridge). A name that always promises more than a beach can deliver.

Devon's rich tapestry of toponyms includes a remarkable number of place names ending in "coombe/combe" and "tor." Both 'coombe' (a word signifying a valley or hollow, directly comparable to the Welsh *cwm* and Cornish *komm*) and 'tor' (derived from Old Welsh *twrr* and Scots Gaelic *tòrr*, ultimately from the Latin *turris* meaning 'tower,' and used to describe distinctive granite formations) are, rather notably, rare [Celtic loanwords in English](/List_of_English_words_of_Welsh_origin). Their frequency reaches its zenith in Devon, a county that, not coincidentally, shares a historical boundary with historically [Brittonic](/Brittonic_languages)-speaking [Cornwall](/Cornwall). The ruined medieval settlements of [Dartmoor longhouses](/Dartmoor_longhouse) provide compelling evidence that the dispersed rural settlement patterns (derived from Old English *tun*, now often found as the suffix '-ton') were strikingly similar to those observed in Cornish 'tre-' settlements. However, these Devonian equivalents are generally described using the local place-name element '-(a)cott,' stemming from the Old English for 'homestead,' a clear precursor to the modern [cottage](/Cottage). Saxon endings incorporating '-worthy' (from the Anglo-Saxon *worthig*) typically denote larger, more substantial settlements. Several instances of 'Bere' indicate ancient Anglo-Saxon wood groves, just as 'leighs' denote clearings in the woodland [61]. Such linguistic echoes, one might argue, offer a profound insight into the very layers of human habitation and land use.

Devon, not content with merely its geography and history, also boasts a vibrant array of festivals and traditional practices, many of which stubbornly persist into the modern era. These include the ancient orchard-visiting [Wassail](/Wassail) ceremony, meticulously observed in [Whimple](/Whimple) every 17 January—a rather specific date for such pagan revelry. Then there is the rather more dangerous tradition of carrying flaming tar barrels in [Ottery St. Mary](/Ottery_St._Mary), where individuals who have demonstrated sufficient longevity of residence in Ottery are, with a certain solemnity, called upon to celebrate [Bonfire Night](/Guy_Fawkes_Night) by running through the village (and, rather alarmingly, through the gathered crowds) with blazing barrels strapped to their backs [62]. A tradition that, one might suggest, combines community spirit with a healthy disregard for health and safety. [Berry Pomeroy](/Berry_Pomeroy) still, rather quaintly, celebrates [Queene's Day](/Queene%27s_Day) in honour of [Elizabeth I](/Elizabeth_I), a nod to a monarch long departed but clearly not forgotten.

## Economy

• Main article: [Economy of Devon](/Economy_of_Devon)

Devon's total economic output in 2019 reportedly exceeded £26 billion, a figure that, somewhat surprisingly, outstripped the economic contributions of either Manchester or Edinburgh [63]. A 2021 report, peering into the intricacies of its economic structure, stated rather plainly that "health, retail and tourism account for 43.1% of employment. Agriculture, education, manufacturing, construction and real estate employment are also over-represented in Devon compared with nationally" [64]. A rather predictable reliance on the service sector, one might observe, for a region famed for its picturesque qualities.

Much like its western neighbour, [Cornwall](/Cornwall), Devon has historically faced economic disadvantages when compared to other, more prosperous parts of [Southern England](/Southern_England). This disparity largely stemmed from the decline of several foundational industries, most notably fishing, mining, and farming. However, the county's economy has, in recent decades, undergone a significant diversification, moving beyond these traditional mainstays. Agriculture, despite its historical struggles, has remained a vital industry in Devon since the 19th century. The devastating [2001 UK foot and mouth crisis](/2001_UK_foot_and_mouth_crisis) inflicted severe damage upon the farming community [65], a wound from which some parts of the agricultural sector have slowly begun to recover and diversify, fostering a robust local food sector and a burgeoning number of artisan producers. Nonetheless, as late as 2015, the dairy industry continued to grapple with the persistently low prices offered for wholesale milk by major dairies and, perhaps more significantly, by large supermarket chains. A testament to the relentless pressures of modern commerce.

The global pandemic, predictably, cast a long and chilling shadow over the economy during 2020 and early 2021. An August 2021 report grimly concluded that "the immediate economic impacts of COVID-19 for the County as a whole [was] as severe as any in living memory" [66]. A rather stark reminder of human fragility in the face of larger forces.

![Part of the seafront of Torquay, south Devon, at high tide](/File:Torquay_seafront.jpg)
Part of the seafront of [Torquay](/Torquay), south Devon, at high tide. A place where leisure and commerce converge, for better or worse.

Between 2014 and 2016, the undeniable allure of the area's lifestyle began to attract new industries, particularly those less constrained by geographical location [67] [68]. [Dartmoor](/Dartmoor), for instance, witnessed a noticeable increase in the proportion of its inhabitants engaged in the digital and financial services sectors—a rather unexpected, if modern, colonisation of the ancient moor. The [Met Office](/Met_Office), the United Kingdom's national and international weather service, relocated its headquarters to [Exeter](/Exeter) in 2003, bringing with it a significant influx of skilled professionals. [Plymouth](/Plymouth) proudly hosts the head office and the very first store of [The Range](/The_Range_(retailer)), making it the only major national retail chain to be headquartered in Devon.

Since the efflorescence of seaside resorts, spurred by the arrival of the railways in the 19th century, Devon's economy has been, for better or worse, heavily reliant on the fickle fortunes of tourism. The county's economy mirrored the general decline observed in British seaside resorts from the mid-20th century onwards. However, a recent, if modest, revival and regeneration of its resorts has been observed, with a particular focus on camping, niche sports such as surfing, cycling, and sailing, and the enduring appeal of heritage. This resurgence has been undeniably aided by the strategic designation of much of Devon's countryside and coastline as the [Dartmoor](/Dartmoor) and [Exmoor](/Exmoor) national parks, and the recognition of the [Jurassic Coast](/Jurassic_Coast) and [Cornwall and West Devon Mining Landscape](/Cornwall_and_West_Devon_Mining_Landscape) as [World Heritage Sites](/World_Heritage_Site). In 2019, the county's visitor spend amounted to almost £2.5 billion [69], a testament to the enduring human desire for temporary escape. More successful visitor attractions are increasingly concentrated on the culinary arts, particularly food and drink, including sea-view restaurants in North-West Devon (one notable example belonging to the artist [Damien Hirst](/Damien_Hurst), if that impresses you). Other popular activities include traversing the [South West Coast Path](/South_West_Coast_Path), cycling along the [Devon Coast to Coast Cycle Route](/Devon_Coast_to_Coast_Cycle_Route) and other dedicated cycle paths such as the [Tarka Trail](/Tarka_Trail) and the Stover Trail, various watersports, surfing, a profusion of indoor and outdoor folk music festivals across the county, and sailing within the picturesque, hill-encircled 5-mile (8.0 km) inlet ([ria](/Ria)) at [Salcombe](/Salcombe).

Incomes across the county exhibit significant variation, with the average often skewed upwards by a disproportionately high number of affluent retired individuals. Incomes in much of the [South Hams](/South_Hams) and in the villages surrounding [Exeter](/Exeter) and [Plymouth](/Plymouth) hover near, or indeed surpass, the national average. Yet, beneath this veneer of prosperity, there exist pockets of severe deprivation, with earnings in some locales among the lowest in the entire United Kingdom. A stark reminder of persistent inequalities.

The accompanying table, for those who find solace in data, illustrates the population change across Devon's subdivisions over the ten years leading up to the [2011 census](/United_Kingdom_Census_2011). It also meticulously details the proportion of residents in each district reliant upon the lowest income and/or joblessness benefits, with the national average proportion standing at 4.5% as of August 2012, the most recent year for which such datasets were published [70]. From this, one can discern that the most populous district of Devon is [East Devon](/East_Devon), but only if one excludes [Torbay](/Torbay), which marginally surpasses it in residents, and [Plymouth](/Plymouth), which boasts approximately double the population of either. [West Devon](/West_Devon), in contrast, holds the distinction of having the fewest residents, numbering 63,839 at the time of the census.

