## Transport

### Bus

A rather extensive network of buses crisscrosses Devon, providing, one hopes, a reliable means of public transport. The largest operator dominating this network is [Stagecoach South West](/Stagecoach_South_West), which, in 2021, rather monopolistically operated a staggering 93% of all services in the county [71]. Smaller, more niche operators include Dartline, Country Bus, and [Plymouth Citybus](/Plymouth_Citybus), offering a modicum of choice.

[Devon County Council](/Devon_County_Council) takes on the rather unenviable task of overseeing and coordinating bus transport through [DevonBus](/DevonBus), an "[Enhanced Partnership](/Bus_Services_Act_2017)" that, in theory, covers the entire county. Its stated purpose is to improve the existing network and, rather optimistically, create a unified brand for buses across Devon [72]. One can only hope that such aspirations translate into actual, tangible improvements for the commuting public.

### Rail

The principal train operator serving Devon is [Great Western Railway](/Great_Western_Railway_(train_operating_company)), which manages a diverse portfolio of regional, local, and suburban services. Additionally, it provides vital inter-city connections, stretching north to [London Paddington](/London_Paddington) and south to [Plymouth](/Plymouth_railway_station) and [Penzance](/Penzance_railway_station). Other inter-city services are operated by [CrossCountry](/CrossCountry), extending their reach north to [Manchester Piccadilly](/Manchester_Piccadilly), [Edinburgh Waverley](/Edinburgh_Waverley), [Glasgow Central](/Glasgow_Central_railway_station), [Dundee](/Dundee_railway_station), and [Aberdeen](/Aberdeen_railway_station), and southwards to Plymouth and Penzance. [South Western Railway](/South_Western_Railway_(train_operating_company)) also contributes to the network, operating hourly services between [London Waterloo](/London_Waterloo) and [Exeter St Davids](/Exeter_St_Davids), utilising the [West of England Main Line](/West_of_England_Main_Line). It is perhaps worth noting, for those who appreciate such technical details, that all train services within Devon are diesel-hauled, as the county remains conspicuously devoid of electrified railway lines.

[Okehampton station](/Okehampton_station) in Devon, a casualty of the infamous [Beeching cuts](/Beeching_cuts), was regrettably closed to passenger traffic in 1972. However, in a rather welcome reversal of fortune, it regained regular passenger services, operated by GWR to [Exeter](/Exeter), in November 2021, a project generously funded by the UK Government's "Restoring your Railway" programme. A small victory for rural connectivity.

Proposals are currently circulating for the reopening of the line from [Tavistock](/Tavistock_railway_station) to [Bere Alston](/Bere_Alston_railway_station), with the ambitious aim of providing a through service to [Plymouth](/Plymouth) [73]. The tantalising possibility of reopening the line between Tavistock and [Okehampton](/Okehampton), which would offer a valuable alternative route between [Exeter](/Exeter) and Plymouth, has also been mooted. This suggestion gained considerable traction following the rather dramatic damage sustained by the railway's [sea wall at Dawlish](/South_Devon_Railway_sea_wall) in 2014, an event that caused widespread disruption to train services between Exeter and [Penzance](/Penzance_railway_station). However, a subsequent study conducted by Network Rail, in a display of pragmatic realism, concluded that maintaining and strengthening the existing railway line would ultimately offer the best value for money [74]. Consequently, work to reinforce the line at [Dawlish](/Dawlish) commenced in 2019 [75]. A testament to the enduring power of cost-benefit analysis.

### Devon Metro

• Main article: [Devon Metro](/Devon_Metro)

[Devon County Council](/Devon_County_Council) has, with a certain ambition, put forth a 'Devon Metro' scheme, a grand design intended to significantly enhance rail services within the county and, rather optimistically, offer a "realistic alternative" to private car travel. This scheme includes the successful opening of [Cranbrook station](/Cranbrook_railway_station_(Devon)) in December 2015, alongside plans for the priority construction of four new stations, including [Edginswell](/Edginswell_railway_station) [76]. Several key elements of this scheme have either been delivered, or are currently in the process of being realised. This includes the construction of [Marsh Barton station](/Marsh_Barton_station) on the periphery of [Exeter](/Exeter) [77], which officially commenced operations in July 2023 [78]. Furthermore, a regular half-hourly local rail service has now been extended from the [Avocet Line](/Avocet_Line), traversing Exeter to encompass the [Riviera Line](/Riviera_Line) [79]. Small steps, perhaps, on the long road to truly effective public transport.

### Air

[Exeter Airport](/Exeter_Airport) remains the sole passenger airport within Devon, having processed over one million travellers in 2019 [80]. Until 2020, [Flybe](/Flybe_(1979-2020)) maintained its headquarters at the airport, a fleeting moment of regional airline prominence. Destinations accessible from Exeter Airport span various locations within the UK (including [London City](/London_City_Airport), Manchester, [Belfast](/Belfast), Edinburgh, and others), as well as a more exotic array of international locales in [Cyprus](/Cyprus), Italy, Netherlands, [Lapland](/Lapland_(Finland)), Portugal, Spain, France, [Malta](/Malta), Switzerland, and Turkey [80]. A rather comprehensive list, for those who require rapid transit beyond the county's borders.

## Education

• Main article: [List of schools in Devon](/List_of_schools_in_Devon)

Devon operates predominantly under a [comprehensive education](/Comprehensive_education) system. Within its borders, there are 37 state-funded secondary schools and 23 independent secondary schools, offering a spectrum of educational choices. The county also hosts three tertiary ([FE](/Further_education)) colleges and a dedicated [agricultural college](/Agricultural_college), [Bicton College](/Bicton_College), conveniently located near [Budleigh Salterton](/Budleigh_Salterton). [Torbay](/Torbay) features eight state secondary schools (three of which are grammar schools) and three independent secondary schools. [Plymouth](/Plymouth), meanwhile, boasts 17 state secondary schools (including three grammar schools—two exclusively for girls and one for boys) and a single independent institution, [Plymouth College](/Plymouth_College). [East Devon](/East_Devon) and [Teignbridge](/Teignbridge) cater to the largest school populations, while [West Devon](/West_Devon) has the smallest, with only two secondary schools. Notably, only one school each in [Exeter](/Exeter), [Mid Devon](/Mid_Devon), [Torridge](/Torridge_District), and [North Devon](/North_Devon) provides a [sixth form](/Sixth_form) (post-16 education); schools in other districts generally offer sixth forms, with all schools in West Devon and East Devon including one. A rather uneven distribution, one might observe.

Three universities have chosen to establish themselves within Devon. The esteemed [University of Exeter](/University_of_Exeter) maintains a presence across its [Streatham Campus](/Streatham_Campus) and [St Luke's Campus](/St_Luke%27s_Campus), both situated in [Exeter](/Exeter), with an additional campus extending into [Cornwall](/Cornwall). In [Plymouth](/Plymouth), the [University of Plymouth](/University_of_Plymouth) stands as a prominent institution of higher learning in Britain, complemented by the [University of St Mark & St John](/University_of_St_Mark_%26_St_John) to the city's north. The Universities of Exeter and Plymouth have, in a commendable display of collaboration, jointly established the [Peninsula College of Medicine and Dentistry](/Peninsula_College_of_Medicine_and_Dentistry), with bases in both Exeter and Plymouth. Finally, for those seeking a more unconventional path, there is also [Schumacher College](/Schumacher_College).

## Cuisine

• Main article: [Cuisine of Devon](/Cuisine_of_Devon)

The county has, rather graciously, lent its name to a selection of culinary specialities. The quintessential Devonshire [cream tea](/Cream_tea), a delightful, if calorific, assembly involving [scones](/Scone_(bread)), [jam](/Jam), and generous dollops of [clotted cream](/Clotted_cream), is widely believed to have originated in Devon (though, predictably, neighbouring counties have also laid claim to this particular invention). In other, more distant lands, such as Australia and New Zealand, it is simply known, with a touch of exoticism, as a "Devonshire tea" [81] [82] [83]. Furthermore, a rather audacious claim has been made that the beloved [pasty](/Pasty) originated not in [Cornwall](/Cornwall), as is commonly believed, but in Devon, with the earliest documented record of a pasty apparently emanating from [Plymouth](/Plymouth) in 1509 [84]. One might consider this a rather provocative assertion, designed to stir up regional rivalries.

In October 2008, Devon was officially bestowed with [Fairtrade County](/Fairtrade_Foundation) status by the [Fairtrade Foundation](/Fairtrade_Foundation) [85] [86]. A noble, if somewhat symbolic, recognition of ethical sourcing.

## Sport

