Devon has historically been a crucible for a variety of distinctive customs and sporting traditions. Among these is its own unique form of [Devon wrestling](/Devon_wrestling), which shares certain similarities with the more widely known [Cornish wrestling](/Cornish_wrestling). As recently as the 19th century, a crowd exceeding 17,000 spectators gathered at Devonport, near [Plymouth](/Plymouth), to witness a gripping match between the champions of Devon and [Cornwall](/Cornwall) [87]—a testament to the enduring regional rivalry. Another ancient Devonian sport was [outhurling](/Cornish_hurling), a robust game that persisted in some regions until the early 20th century (for example, in 1922, at [Great Torrington](/Great_Torrington)) [88]. Other ancient customs that stubbornly refuse to fade into obscurity include Dartmoor step dancing and the evocative ritual of "[Crying The Neck](/Crying_The_Neck)."

Devon is currently home to three professional [association football](/Association_football) teams, each strategically located in its most populous towns and cities. As of the 2025 season, [Plymouth Argyle F.C.](/Plymouth_Argyle_F.C.) and [Exeter City F.C.](/Exeter_City_F.C.) both compete in the demanding [EFL League One](/EFL_League_One), while [Torquay United F.C.](/Torquay_United_F.C.) plies its trade in the [National League](/National_League_(division)). Plymouth's highest ever finish in the Football League was an impressive fourth place in the [Second Division](/Football_League_Second_Division), a feat achieved twice, in 1932 and again in 1953. In contrast, Torquay and Exeter have never managed to ascend beyond the third tier of the league structure; Torquay famously finished second on [goal average](/Goal_average) in the [Third Division (S)](/Football_League_Third_Division) in 1957, narrowly missing out to Sir [Alf Ramsey](/Alf_Ramsey)'s [Ipswich Town](/Ipswich_Town). Exeter's highest position has been eighth in the Third Division (S). The county's most prominent non-league clubs include [Plymouth Parkway F.C.](/Plymouth_Parkway_F.C.) and [Tiverton Town F.C.](/Tiverton_Town_F.C.), both competing in the [Southern Football League Premier Division](/Southern_Football_League_Premier_Division), alongside [Bideford A.F.C.](/Bideford_A.F.C.), [Exmouth Town F.C.](/Exmouth_Town_F.C.), and [Tavistock A.F.C.](/Tavistock_A.F.C.), who are all currently in the [Southern Football League Division One South and West](/Southern_Football_League_Division_One_South_and_West). A rather intricate hierarchy, one might observe, for the beautiful game.

[Rugby Union](/Rugby_Union) enjoys considerable popularity within Devon, evidenced by over forty clubs operating under the umbrella of the [Devon Rugby Football Union](/Devon_Rugby_Football_Union), many of which field multiple teams across senior, youth, and junior levels. One club, [Exeter Chiefs](/Exeter_Chiefs), holds the prestigious position of playing in the [Aviva Premiership](/English_Premiership_(rugby_union)), having claimed the title in 2017 for the first time in their history after a hard-fought victory against [Wasps RFC](/Wasps_RFC) in the final, with a score of 23–20. [Plymouth Albion](/Plymouth_Albion), as of the 2023 update, competes in the [National League 1](/National_League_1), which represents the third tier of English Professional Rugby Union.

For those who prefer a different oval-ball code, there are five [rugby league](/Rugby_league) teams in Devon: [Plymouth Titans](/Plymouth_Titans), [Exeter Centurions](/Exeter_Centurions), and [Devon Sharks](/Devon_Sharks) from [Torquay](/Torquay), the North Devon Raiders from [Barnstaple](/Barnstaple), and the [East Devon Eagles](/East_Devon_Eagles) from [Exmouth](/Exmouth). All of these teams participate in the [Rugby League Conference](/Rugby_League_Conference).

[Plymouth City Patriots](/Plymouth_City_Patriots) proudly represent Devon in the [British Basketball League](/British_Basketball_League). Formed in 2021, they effectively replaced the former professional club, [Plymouth Raiders](/Plymouth_Raiders), after the latter team was regrettably withdrawn from competition due to persistent venue issues [89]. [Motorcycle speedway](/Motorcycle_speedway) also garners support within the county, with both the [Exeter Falcons](/Exeter_Falcons) and [Plymouth Gladiators](/Plymouth_Gladiators) achieving success in the National Leagues in recent years.

The [University of Exeter Hockey Club](/University_of_Exeter_Hockey_Club) fields teams in both the [Men's](/Men%27s_England_Hockey_League) and [Women's England Hockey Leagues](/Women%27s_England_Hockey_League), demonstrating a commitment to academic and athletic pursuits.

[Horse Racing](/Horse_racing) maintains a popular following in the county, which boasts two [National Hunt](/National_Hunt) racecourses (at [Exeter](/Exeter) and [Newton Abbot](/Newton_Abbot)), alongside numerous [point-to-point](/Point_to_point_(steeplechase)) courses. Furthermore, Devon is home to many successful professional racehorse trainers, a testament to its equestrian heritage.

The county is represented in the venerable sport of [cricket](/Cricket) by [Devon County Cricket Club](/Devon_County_Cricket_Club), which competes at a [Minor counties](/Minor_counties_of_English_and_Welsh_cricket) level.

## Notable Devonians

• Main article: [Notable people from Devon](/Notable_people_from_Devon)

![Agatha Christie, best selling crime novelist](/File:Agatha_Christie_portrait_cropped.jpg)
[Agatha Christie](/Agatha_Christie), best-selling crime novelist. A mind that understood the darker corners of human nature, perhaps cultivated by the quiet mysteries of Devon.

![Chris Martin, lead singer of Coldplay](/File:Chris_Martin_-_Glastonbury_2016_cropped.jpg)
[Chris Martin](/Chris_Martin), lead singer of [Coldplay](/Coldplay). From the serene landscapes of Devon to the global stage, a rather significant leap.

![Roger Deakins, multi-award winning cinematographer](/File:Roger_Deakins_BAFTA_2018.jpg)
[Roger Deakins](/Roger_Deakins), multi-award winning cinematographer. His eye for light and shadow, perhaps honed by the dramatic skies of his home county.

![Ollie Watkins, plays football for England](/File:Ollie_Watkins_2024.jpg)
[Ollie Watkins](/Ollie_Watkins), plays football for [England](/England_national_football_team). Another talent nurtured by Devon, then unleashed upon the world.

Devon is, rather famously, known for its distinguished cadre of [mariners](/Mariner), individuals whose lives were inextricably linked with the sea and the boundless horizons it offered. This illustrious list includes figures such as [Sir Francis Drake](/Sir_Francis_Drake), [Sir Humphrey Gilbert](/Sir_Humphrey_Gilbert), [Sir Richard Grenville](/Sir_Richard_Grenville), [Sir Walter Raleigh](/Sir_Walter_Raleigh), [Sir Francis Chichester](/Sir_Francis_Chichester), and [Sir William Robert Patrick Knox-Johnston](/Sir_William_Robert_Patrick_Knox-Johnston) [90]. [Henry Every](/Henry_Every), a name whispered with a certain dread, often described as the most notorious pirate of the late 17th century, was most likely born in the unassuming village of [Newton Ferrers](/Newton_Ferrers) [91]. [John Oxenham](/John_Oxenham) (1536–1580), a lieutenant under Drake, found himself branded a pirate by the Spanish, a common occupational hazard of the era. [Thomas Morton](/Thomas_Morton_(colonist)) (1576–1647), an avid Elizabethan outdoorsman likely born in Devon, later became an attorney for The Council For New England and established the New England fur-trading plantation known as Ma-Re Mount or Merrymount, complete with a West Country-style Maypole, much to the consternation of the more austere Pilgrim and Puritan colonists. Morton, in his 1637 book *New English Canaan*, penned an account of his experiences, partly in verse, thereby potentially becoming America's first poet to write in English [92]. Another prominent mariner and Devonian was [Robert Falcon Scott](/Robert_Falcon_Scott), the ill-fated leader of the [Terra Nova Expedition](/Terra_Nova_Expedition) to the geographical South Pole [93]. Their stories, one might observe, are etched into the very maritime history of the nation.

The acting world has also drawn talent from Devon. The acclaimed actor [Matthew Goode](/Matthew_Goode) was raised within the county's serene landscapes, and [Bradley James](/Bradley_James), another actor of note, was born there. In the realm of music, the soulful singer [Joss Stone](/Joss_Stone) grew up in Devon, while [Chris Martin](/Chris_Martin), the frontman of the globally renowned British rock group [Coldplay](/Coldplay), first saw the light of day there. [Matt Bellamy](/Matt_Bellamy), [Dominic Howard](/Dominic_Howard), and [Chris Wolstenholme](/Chris_Wolstenholme), the core members of the English group [Muse](/Muse_(band)), all spent their formative years in Devon and, crucially, formed their band within its borders. Dave Hill of the iconic rock band [Slade](/Slade) was born at [Flete House](/Flete_House) in the [South Hams](/South_Hams) district of Devon. The acclaimed singer-songwriter [Ben Howard](/Ben_Howard) spent his childhood in [Totnes](/Totnes), a charming small town in Devon. Another notable Devonian is the model and actress [Rosie Huntington-Whiteley](/Rosie_Huntington-Whiteley), born in [Plymouth](/Plymouth) and raised in [Tavistock](/Tavistock). The singer and songwriter [Rebecca Newman](/Rebecca_Newman) was both born and raised in [Exmouth](/Exmouth) [94]. [Roger Deakins](/Roger_Deakins), a man frequently lauded as "the pre-eminent [cinematographer](/Cinematographer) of our time," was born in Devon and, rather tellingly, continues to reside there [95]. The county, it seems, has a knack for nurturing creative minds.

In the sporting arena, [Ollie Watkins](/Ollie_Watkins), a professional [footballer](/Association_football) of considerable repute, was born in Devon [96]. Similarly, the legendary footballer [Trevor Francis](/Trevor_Francis) was raised within the county [97]. The Olympic swimmer [Sharron Davies](/Sharron_Davies) [98] and the celebrated diver [Tom Daley](/Tom_Daley) [99] both trace their origins to [Plymouth](/Plymouth). The accomplished Olympic runner [Jo Pavey](/Jo_Pavey) was born in [Honiton](/Honiton). [Peter Cook](/Peter_Cook), the satirist, writer, and comedian whose wit cut through the absurdities of his age, was born in [Torquay](/Torquay), Devon. [Leicester Tigers](/Leicester_Tigers) and [British and Irish Lions](/British_and_Irish_Lions) Rugby player [Julian White](/Julian_White) was born and raised in Devon and now, in a rather pastoral turn, farms a herd of pedigree South Devon beef cattle. The renowned dog breeder [John "Jack" Russell](/John_%22Jack%22_Russell), whose name is now synonymous with a particular breed, also hailed from Devon. [Jane McGrath](/Jane_McGrath), who married the Australian cricketer [Glenn McGrath](/Glenn_McGrath), was born in [Paignton](/Paignton); her prolonged battle with, and eventual death from, breast cancer inspired the creation of the [McGrath Foundation](/McGrath_Foundation), which has become one of Australia's leading charities. A legacy, one might note, far greater than any sporting achievement.

Devon has also served as a home, source of inspiration, or operational base for a multitude of other notable writers, artists, [entrepreneurs](/Entrepreneur), and politicians. The poet [Samuel Taylor Coleridge](/Samuel_Taylor_Coleridge), the celebrated crime writers [Agatha Christie](/Agatha_Christie) and [Bertram Fletcher Robinson](/Bertram_Fletcher_Robinson), the Irish writer [William Trevor](/William_Trevor), and the poet [Ted Hughes](/Ted_Hughes) each, at various points, chose to reside in Devon. The eminent painter and founder of the [Royal Academy](/Royal_Academy), [Sir Joshua Reynolds](/Sir_Joshua_Reynolds), was born in Devon. [Chris Dawson](/Chris_Dawson_(businessman)), the billionaire owner of the retail giant [The Range](/The_Range_(retailer)), was born in Devon, and his business, rather loyally, maintains its head office in [Plymouth](/Plymouth). Politically, Devon has been represented in the [House of Commons](/House_of_Commons_of_the_United_Kingdom) by notable [Members of Parliament](/Member_of_Parliament_(United_Kingdom)) (MPs) such as [Nancy Astor](/Nancy_Astor), [Gwyneth Dunwoody](/Gwyneth_Dunwoody), [Michael Foot](/Michael_Foot), and [David Owen](/David_Owen), as well as two former Prime Ministers, [Lord John Russell](/Lord_John_Russell) and [Lord Palmerston](/Lord_Palmerston). A rather impressive roster, for a county that often seems content to simply exist.

